## III. THE COHERENCE VARIABLE: WHERE CONSCIOUSNESS BECOMES ENGINEERING

The most novel component of the IISL is **C** — coherence — because it transforms consciousness from a philosophical question into an engineering parameter.

The formalization comes from Integrated Information Theory (IIT), developed by neuroscientist Giulio Tononi. IIT proposes that consciousness corresponds to a system's integrated information Φ — the degree to which the system's cause-effect structure is intrinsic, specific, unified, definite, and structured. The Φ-structure unfolded from a complex corresponds to the quality of consciousness, and the sum of φ values corresponds to its quantity. [PubMed Central](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10581496/)

The critical engineering insight is this: biological nervous systems such as the brain achieve very high Φ because neurons have thousands of connections to one another, while a typical circuit in a standard CPU makes only a few connections to other circuits, limiting its potential Φ value considerably. [Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy](https://iep.utm.edu/integrated-information-theory-of-consciousness/)

In plain terms: **silicon is architecturally incapable of high coherence by design.** Its discrete, modular, feedforward structure — the very thing that makes it fast — prevents the kind of irreducible causal integration that generates unified conscious experience. The IISL predicts that any intelligence built on low-Φ architecture will hit a coherence ceiling regardless of how much compute it adds.

Carbon-based biological systems do not face this ceiling. They are, structurally, Φ-maximizing systems. The question is whether we can engineer them to reach their theoretical maximum.

