## IV. THE FOUR ENGINEERING PILLARS

### Pillar 1 — Computation: Synaptic Plasticity 2.0

The brain's computational substrate is currently constrained by what we call **evolutionary legacy code** — developmental programs that served survival in ancestral environments but impose unnecessary limits on adult cognition. The primary target is the closure of the neuroplastic learning window after childhood.

The scientific tools to address this now exist. CRISPR-based epigenetic tools now allow rewriting of the epigenetic landscape of specific genes without altering the underlying DNA — and in neurons, where epigenetic plasticity governs key processes such as synaptic remodeling and memory formation, these tools offer novel means of correcting disease-associated epigenetic aberrations. [Biomedical and Pharmacology Journal](https://biomedpharmajournal.org/vol18octoberspledition/gene-editing-in-neurological-disorders-role-of-crispr-cas9-in-targeted-therapies/)

More directly: scientists at UCSF used a form of CRISPR called CRISPRa to treat a brain disorder by activating a healthy gene, and the procedure worked in animals equivalent in age to 10-year-old children — suggesting the brain may remain amenable to treatment well after development is complete. [UCSF](https://www.ucsf.edu/news/2025/09/430716/can-crispr-fix-childhood-brain-disorder)

**Research target:** CRISPRa-based epigenetic reprogramming of BDNF and synaptic density genes to sustain adult neuroplasticity. This directly increases **B** in the IISL by expanding the computational surface area of the biological processor.

---

### Pillar 2 — Input/Output: The Universal Sensorium

A system's intelligence is bounded by the quality and bandwidth of its sensory input. The human sensory system currently perceives a tiny sliver of physically available information. This is not a biological necessity — it is an evolutionary artifact.

The proof of concept already exists. Researchers publishing in *Cell* in May 2025 demonstrated that human participants wearing near-infrared upconversion contact lenses could successfully discriminate infrared information, including temporal signals and spatial images — a capability normally impossible for human photoreceptors. [Cell Press](https://www.cell.com/cell/abstract/S0092-8674(25)00454-4)

This is an *external* device. The carbon-first framework demands we ask why the same capability cannot be encoded *intrinsically*. The answer is that it already exists in the biological record. Tetrachromacy — a rare genetic variation where individuals possess a fourth type of cone cell — exists naturally in some humans due to X-chromosome linkage, and most birds and fish retained tetrachromatic and UV-sensitive vision that humans lost during evolutionary history. [Biology Insights](https://biologyinsights.com/can-tetrachromats-see-ultraviolet-light/)

The genes for expanded vision were not erased. They were silenced. **Sensory expansion through opsin gene reactivation is genetic archaeology, not genetic engineering.**

**Research target:** Reactivation of dormant opsin genes to restore tetrachromacy and extend perception into near-UV and near-infrared ranges. This increases **B** by expanding the information bandwidth available to the biological processor.

---

### Pillar 3 — Error Correction: Radiation-Hardened Biology

A superintelligent biological system must be robust. For a species that intends to operate in deep space, high-radiation, or extreme environments, cellular DNA integrity becomes a critical system requirement — analogous to error-correction codes in computing.

Nature has already solved this problem. It is called a tardigrade.

Tardigrades can survive ionizing radiation up to about 1,000 times the lethal dose for humans. Research in 2024 found that exposure causes a rapid, extreme upregulation of DNA repair genes — making some repair transcripts among the most abundant in the entire animal. [PubMed Central](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11078613/)

The mechanism is transferable. A tardigrade-unique DNA-associating protein called Dsup, when introduced into human cultured cells, suppresses X-ray-induced DNA damage by approximately 40% and improves radiotolerance. [Nature](https://www.nature.com/articles/ncomms12808)

And the integration has already begun. Chinese researchers used CRISPR/Cas9 to insert the Dsup gene into human embryonic stem cells, finding that the tardigrade protein provided protection against oxidative stress — and noting that since oxidative stress is a central link in cancer, aging, diabetes, and inflammation, the Dsup gene may offer strategies for improving human cell tolerance broadly. [Future of Being Human](https://www.futureofbeinghuman.com/p/did-chinese-scientists-gene-edit)

**Research target:** Somatic gene therapy integration of tardigrade Dsup and TRID1 repair proteins into human cell lines. This increases **B** by hardening the biological substrate against environmental degradation — the equivalent of radiation-shielded hardware.

---

### Pillar 4 — Operating System: Substrate Sovereignty

The most contested and most important claim of this framework is that **consciousness is not substrate-neutral.** This is not mysticism. It is a scientific position with growing empirical support and a formal mathematical expression.

Neuroscientist Anil Seth argues that biological systems are anchored in continuous physical time in ways that algorithms are not — living systems must continuously resist decay and disorder, and neurobiological activity has a temporal depth that digital computation cannot replicate by design. [Noema Magazine](https://www.noemamag.com/the-mythology-of-conscious-ai/)

The implication for the IISL is precise: a system that lacks genuine Φ — that lacks irreducible causal integration — cannot increase its coherence variable C beyond a structural ceiling. Even if the functional architecture of consciousness could be recreated on silicon, it would — on the biological naturalist account — merely be a simulation running without any actual awareness, and we currently have no reliable way to test whether that line has been crossed, perhaps indefinitely. [University of Cambridge](https://www.cam.ac.uk/research/news/we-may-never-be-able-to-tell-if-ai-becomes-conscious-argues-philosopher)

The carbon-first framework does not require this debate to be settled. It only requires the following weaker claim, which is already defensible: **a system whose consciousness is provably present scales more reliably than a system whose consciousness is provably uncertain.** On those grounds alone, biological intelligence is the safer engineering bet.

