## V. THE THERMODYNAMIC CONSTRAINT: WHY THIS IS NOT SCIENCE FICTION

Every serious theory must state its limits. The IISL is governed by a hard constraint:

> **Intrinsic scaling must obey biological thermodynamics. Therefore, optimization — not expansion — is its governing principle.**

The brain cannot simply grow larger or run hotter. Oxygen delivery, glucose metabolism, and heat dissipation impose hard ceilings on raw computational expansion. This is why the IISL is framed as B × C / E — the optimization target is the **ratio**, not the numerator alone. A brain that doubles its integration while halving its energy waste has achieved a genuine scaling event. A brain that simply consumes more is not scaling; it is burning.

Recent work in information physics demonstrates a critical phase transition point in intelligent systems, below which memory retrieval is thermodynamically favorable and above which generative computation becomes optimal — suggesting that minimization of derivation entropy is a governing principle for the evolution of both biological and artificial intelligence. [arXiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2511.19156)

This is exactly the principle the IISL encodes. The biological path does not pursue unlimited growth. It pursues **maximum intelligence per unit of thermodynamic cost**. This is not a weakness. It is the most elegant engineering constraint in the known universe — and the human brain is already its best known solution.

